hands_on_practices.solution:
Let $X \sim U(0,\theta)$ with density $f(x;\theta)=\frac{1}{\theta}$ for $0x\theta$. The cumulative distribution function for $0x\theta$ is
$$
F(x;\theta)=\mathbb{P}_{\theta}(X\leq x)=\int_{0}^{x}\frac{1}{\theta}\,dt=\frac{x}{\theta}.
$$
The test rejects $H_{0}$ when $X0.95$, where $0.95=\frac{19}{20}$. The power at parameter $\theta$ is
$$
\pi(\theta)=\mathbb{P}_{\theta}(X\tfrac{19}{20})=
\begin{cases}
0,  \theta\leq \tfrac{19}{20} \\
1-F(\tfrac{19}{20};\theta)=1-\dfrac{\tfrac{19}{20}}{\theta},  \theta\tfrac{19}{20}
\end{cases}
$$
Under the alternative $H_{a}:\theta1$, we have $\theta\tfrac{19}{20}$, so
$$
\pi(\theta)=1-\frac{\tfrac{19}{20}}{\theta}.
$$
Set the power equal to $\frac{1}{2}$ and solve for $\theta$:
$$
1-\frac{\tfrac{19}{20}}{\theta}=\frac{1}{2}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{\tfrac{19}{20}}{\theta}=\frac{1}{2}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{19}{20\theta}=\frac{1}{2}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
19=10\theta
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\theta=\frac{19}{10}.
$$
This value satisfies $\theta1$, hence it is admissible under $H_{a}$.
